  "prompt": "What is meant by one standard deviation above the mean?",
  "response": "In statistics, \"one standard deviation above the mean\" refers to a point on a data distribution that is exactly one standard deviation greater than the average (mean) value.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n1. The mean is the average of all values in a dataset\n2. Standard deviation measures how spread out the data points are from the mean\n3. One standard deviation above the mean means moving up from the average by exactly one standard deviation value\n\nFor example:\n- If the mean is 50\n- And the standard deviation is 10\n- One standard deviation above the mean would be 60 (50 + 10)\n\nIn a normal distribution:\n- About 68% of data falls within one standard deviation of the mean\n- About 95% falls within two standard deviations\n- About 99.7% falls within three standard deviations\n\nThis concept is useful in understanding data variation and making statistical comparisons.",
